        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The month and year are established by the address. The Darwins stayed with their son <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1226.xml">Horace</ref> and his wife, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1227.xml">Ida Darwin</ref>, in Cambridge from 20 to 27 October 1881 (CD’s ‘Journal’ (Appendix II)).  </note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13474F.xml">letter from Francis Darwin, [21 October 1881]</ref> and n. 3. Francis was thinking of reviewing <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_11461.xml">Wiesner 1881</ref>. The other work by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5122.xml">Julius Wiesner</ref> was ‘Die heliotropischen Erscheinungen im Pflanzenreiche’ (Heliotropic phenomena in the plant world; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10441.xml">Wiesner 1878–80</ref>). CD had read an abstract of the work in 1878 and later cited it in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5637.xml"><hi rend="italic">Movement in plants</hi></ref>, p. 12 (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 26, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11615.xml">letter to Francis Darwin, 17 July [1878]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_11461.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">Wiesner 1881</ref>, p. 141.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_11461.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">Wiesner 1881</ref>, pp. 107–29; Wiesner concluded that the phenomenon was a combination of negative geotropism (movement in opposition to gravity) and apheliotropism (movement away from light).</note>            
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">CD’s notes on the effects of removing the leader or lateral shoots or both in the Caucasian fir (<hi rend="italic">Picea nordmanniana</hi>, a synonym of <hi rend="italic">Abies nordmanniana</hi> subsp. <hi rend="italic">nordmanniana</hi>) and silver fir (<hi rend="italic">Abies pectinata</hi>, a synonym of <hi rend="italic">A. alba</hi>), dated between 14 July 1879 and 26 January 1880, are in DAR 209: 6.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5637.xml"><hi rend="italic">Movement in plants</hi></ref>, pp. 489–91.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7">Francis had sent a specimen of an unnamed species of <hi rend="italic">Pinguicula</hi> (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13474F.xml">letter from Francis Darwin, [21 October 1881]</ref> and n. 5); no experimental notes around this time on <hi rend="italic">Pinguicula</hi> have been identified.</note>  
        </div>
    
